      "writtenOn": "2020-02-19T16:39:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Using a signed value does not mean it can\u0027t overflow. Int overflow is undefined behavior, so the compiler can assume you took measures to avoid undefined behavior. Since we are using 2s-complement an overflow becomes negative. So, to avoid undefined behavior you must check for overflow.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 29,
        "startChar": 6,
        "endLine": 29,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "0f07852559ae13534d16236aeec9fbb584800b99",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c7210392_fafa4db5",
        "filename": "src/gpu/GrBlockAllocator.h",
        "patchSetId": 26
      },
      "lineNbr": 29,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-19T18:23:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I did not mean to imply that because it\u0027s a signed value means it\u0027s not overflowing, but that because we impose a smaller upper bound that is checked in allocate(), that we can then reason about the range of signed int values that are produced during the arithmetic, and statically assert that none of those would overflow given the one runtime check that is performed.\n\nBecause we have that assert, it is then convenient to switch to signed ints instead of size_t for any small performance gain that might bring.",
      "parentUuid": "18118f94_0877cf27",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 29,
        "startChar": 6,
        "endLine": 29,
        "endChar": 28
